=09=09=09=09Amid signs that America=01,s economy is slowing, Alan Greenspan=
, chairman of the=20
Federal Reserve, admitted that inflation was no longer his primary concern.=
=20
He also hinted that he would act if the economy slowed too sharply. Markets=
=20
interpreted this as a sign that the Fed would soon cut interest rates.=20
America=01,s tech-heavy Nasdaq jumped by 10%, its biggest-ever daily gain, =
and=20
the Dow Jones Industrial Average went up by 3%, though both fell back a bit=
=20
the next day.
=09=09=09=09See article: A hard landing?
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09The IMF offered new loans of $7.5 billion (and a total package =
worth $10.4=20
billion) to Turkey, in an attempt to contain Turkey=01,s financial and bank=
ing=20
crisis. The IMF is also negotiating new loans to Argentina, another trouble=
d=20
emerging economy.
=09=09=09=09See article: Turkey and the IMFE+
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Gerhard Schr"der, Germany=01,s chancellor, said that Russian de=
bt owed to=20
Germany (around half of the total of $48 billion owed to the Paris Club of=
=20
western governments) could be swapped for stakes in Russian companies. As a=
=20
long-term solution, this has merits; but next year Russia is scheduled to=
=20
repay $3.9 billion, and has so far allocated only a quarter of this sum.
=09=09=09=09See article: Russian capital loves to travelE+
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Japan=01,s GDP grew by only 1.0% at an annual rate in the third=
 quarter, a=20
similar rate to the previous quarter, after growth had surged at the start =
of=20
the year. Japan has introduced a new system for calculating GDP, although i=
t=20
may be no more reliable than previous methods.=20
