=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Reuters, a British media group, announced a successor to replac=
e Peter Job as=20
chief executive when he retires next July. Tom Glocer, head of Reuters=01, =
main=20
information division, will become the first American (and first=20
non-journalist) to run the company.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09The revival of Apple Computer, overseen by Steve Jobs, chief ex=
ecutive and=20
co-founder, suffered a sharp setback after a profits warning. The company=
=20
expects a loss in the quarter to the end of the year, and its revenues are=
=20
trailing behind forecasts.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09British Telecom sold bonds worth $10 billion, offering high yie=
lds to=20
compensate for its ballooning debt and rickety credit rating. Initial publi=
c=20
offerings by Norway=01,s Telenor and Portugal Telecom both fell below their=
=20
offer prices when trading began.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Nokia, the world=01,s leading mobile-phone maker, said that rev=
enues were likely=20
to remain strong until 2003 and that the world would see its one-billionth=
=20
mobile subscriber by early 2002, rather than the end of this year. Nokia al=
so=20
dismissed suggestions that WAP and other Internet-enabled devices would not=
=20
catch on.
